...............................................
[4
Date: Sun, 14 Sep 1997 01:44:55 -0400 (EDT)
From: Dr Zero@aol.com

Ahi Tuna is a Sushi/Sashimi dish in local Japanese Sushi bars. I have been
eating this seered ahi tuna for 3-4 years at various times. I have seen it
served at a Ritz Carlton Hotel in Laguna Niguel for a Orange County Wine
Tasting Meeting. Mostly it is served as a gourmet food. I have not seen
it served as an indication of the freshness and safe handling
representation of a restaurant.
True, Anasikiasis and such is possible from raw fish, but what are the real
incidence of these parasitic diseases? There is a lot of raw or
undercooked meat and fish served in Japanese (and other) restaurants, but
primarily Sushi Bars, throughout the United States, They are very popular
here on the West Coast! Seems there are large numbers consuming such food.
But what percent are likely to be infected? Are there any real numbers
available?
--
Peter Cyrog, DVM
Los Angeles, Calif. USA
Dr Zero@aol.com
...........................................
[5
Date: Mon, 15 Sep 1997 08:07:39 +0700 (GMT+0700)
From: "Nelia P. Salazar " <alnps@gold.diamond.mahidol.ac.th>
I have always enjoyed "naem" (sausage made of fermented raw pork and all
the goodies) in Thailand since the 1960s. So far, I have not contracted
trichinosis nor taeniasis ('keeping my fingers crossed though). The
prevalence of zoonotic/parasitic contamination in food products such as
this may be low. The probability of acquiring human infections from these
food products is like lottery - except that being a jackpot winner is not
the desired end.

[Thanks to the many people who wrote in to correct my slip concerning viral
causes of foodborne illnesses. I did indeed mean to say Hepatitis E rather
than Hepatitis C. Other considerations are also mentioned below. One of
the great things about moderating ProMED-mail is that you are absolutely
